                <note rend="inline" type="source">
                    <persName corresp="#p_EDD1">Eisenhower</persName> Library, <persName
                        corresp="#p_HJC1">James C. Hagerty</persName> papers</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">
                        <persName corresp="#p_HJC1">Hagerty</persName> Diary, March 26, 1954</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date ana="#date_undated-inferred-from-document-head"
                            calendar="gregorian" when="1954-03-26">undated</date>.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <note rend="inline" type="source">[Extract]</note>
                <p>. . . . . . .</p>
                <p rend="flushleft">
                    <hi rend="italic">Cabinet Meeting</hi>
                </p>
                <p>1. <hi rend="italic">Dulles</hi> reviewed Indo-China situation—said we must help
                    Fr. win in Indo-China—if not, Reds would win that part of world and “cut our
                    defense line in half”—predicted U.S. may have to take “fairly strong
                    action”—involving risks—”but these risks will be less if we take them now rather
                    than waiting for several years”—said Fr. should give political sovereignty to
                    Associated States—Fr. want our help, but not in any form they think might damage
                    their prestige in area—we should train local troops and work for freedom for
                    states—fighting season to stop in about 30 days—but “serious
                        situation”—<persName corresp="#p_LHC1">Cabot Lodge</persName> asked if
                    couldn’t turn Indo-China into another Greece, where we trained and helped
                    them—Pres. said situation different—Greeks were sturdy people with will to win,
                    Vietnam “backward people” who don’t think Fr. sincere in granting them
                    freedom—”France presents difficult questions everywhere you look.”</p>
                <p>. . . . . . .</p>
            </div>
